    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix crash in F1AP Reset Acknowledge handling when no UEs present\n\n### Summary\nThe F1AP Reset Acknowledge message processing crashes when handling messages with zero UEs to reset. This occurs because the decoder incorrectly asserts that at least one UE must be present, and the equality comparison function doesn't properly handle NULL pointer cases.\n\nThis fix modifies three functions to properly handle the case when there are no UEs in the Reset Acknowledge message.\n\n### Changes\n- `openair2/F1AP/lib/f1ap_interface_management.c`: \n  - Modified `decode_f1ap_reset_ack()` to remove incorrect assertion and handle zero UEs case\n  - Modified `eq_f1ap_reset_ack()` to safely check pointers before dereferencing\n  - Modified `free_f1ap_reset_ack()` to check for NULL before freeing\n\n### Reproduction\nTo reproduce the issue:\n1. Configure gNB to send F1AP Reset Acknowledge with zero UEs\n2. Observe segfault in `decode_f1ap_reset_ack()` due to assertion failure\n3. Alternatively, create two `f1ap_reset_ack_t` structures with `num_ue_to_reset=0` and `ue_to_reset=NULL` and call `eq_f1ap_reset_ack()` - may cause crash depending on memory layout\n\nThe fix ensures these functions handle the zero UE case gracefully without crashing.\n"
}